</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
207 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ETHNIC CONFLICT IN EAST BLOC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I think that it is very difficult for Americans to comprehend the idea of 
nationalism. Our population is so diverse that the prevalent philosophy is one 
of un-nationalism. 
</P>
<P>
But when we look at events in other countries, there is a different story. 
</P>
<P>
It is obvious that the attempt to "Sovietize" the population within the Soviet 
Union did not work. To understand why this was a failure, one has to thoroughly 
understand the individual histories of the 14 non-Russian countries -- not the 
Russian versions of these histories. 
</P>
<P>
The emergence of the Soviet Union did not solve the territorial problems by 
examining the roots of these conflicts and offering solutions; imposition of 
the Soviet system was like placing a Band-Aid over a wound which needed more 
sophisticated treatment. 
</P>
<P>
With some loosening of this oppressive system, the smoldering fires of 
nationalism flared up once again. The "ghosts in the attic" are not dangerous 
ghosts. Nationalism is actually a very healthy state and people should be 
masters on their own territories. 
</P>
<P>
Unlike the comments made by Alexiev, nationalism has always been on the 
forefront. It did not re-emerge suddenly with glasnost and perestroika. 
</P>
<P>
CHLOE ROSE PARKER 
</P>
<P>
West Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
