<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANDINISTAS FREE 1,190 IMPRISONED FOR POLITICS; 
</P>
<P>
NICARAGUA: SOME VIEW THE MOVE TWO WEEKS BEFORE THE PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION AS A 
PLOY TO WIN VOTES FOR ORTEGA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARJORIE MILLER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TIPITAPA, Nicaragua 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two weeks before national elections, the Sandinista government on Friday freed 
1,190 Contras, rebel collaborators and former National Guardsmen in a prison 
yard ceremony that officials said emptied Nicaraguan jails of all political 
prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
Among the 39 National Guardsmen released were allegedly some of the most brutal 
officers from the dictatorship of Anastasio Somoza, who was deposed by a 
Sandinista-led insurrection in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
Sandinista officials charged, for instance, that when Col. Isaias Cuadra served 
as director of the Tipitapa Penitentiary under Somoza, he tortured at least one 
prominent prisoner -- Sandinista Cmdr. Tomas Borge. Since the Sandinistas came 
to power, Borge has served as interior minister, overseeing the prisons, and 
Cuadra has spent 10 1/2 years in jail. 
</P>
<P>
"I have suffered a great deal during these years I have spent in prison," 
Cuadra, 56, said on his release. "I have come to understand human beings. I 
understand there are passions, there is pain and that anyone who is a Christian 
has to know how to forgive." 
</P>
<P>
But he denied having tortured anyone, although reports of torture under Somoza 
were common. 
</P>
<P>
President Daniel Ortega, who also spent time in jail for being a Sandinista 
guerrilla, had announced the release last month as a gesture to reunite this 
country, which has been divided first by the Sandinista revolution and then by 
the U.S.-backed Contra war. 
</P>
<P>
Under the Central American peace accords signed by the region's five 
presidents, the Sandinistas are required to pardon and release political 
prisoners. But Ortega is seeking reelection Feb. 25 as the Sandinista National 
Liberation Front's candidate for peace and reconciliation, and the release is 
seen by many as a campaign maneuver to win votes. 
</P>
<P>
Cmdr. Franco Montealegre, head of prisons, read the release decree as the 
convicts stood in single file on the prison yard's concrete basketball courts. 
Diplomats, members of the media and international observers here to monitor the 
elections watched the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government must respond to this decree by stopping its support for 
warlike options and by giving determined support to the peace process," the 
decree stated. 
</P>
<P>
Four former Contra commanders who have come back to Nicaragua to observe the 
elections also attended the ceremony. When Montealegre greeted them during his 
introduction, the prisoners broke into applause. 
</P>
<P>
Many of the Contras and guardsmen interviewed after receiving their release 
papers said they hope to move to the United States, where most of their 
relatives live. 
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing for me here," said former National Guard Capt. Orlando Hislop 
Mercado, 45. 
</P>
<P>
Sandinista officials accuse Hislop of having raped and tortured Cmdr. Doris 
Tijerino during her imprisonment as a guerrilla. Now, Tijerino is head of the 
Sandinista police. 
</P>
<P>
"I have been accused of everything you can imagine. My release order says 
'atrocious assassination.' I heard on the radio the other day that I had raped 
a commander. I don't even know all they accuse me of, but . . . all the 
accusations are false," Hislop said. 
</P>
<P>
Another of the released former guardsmen was Maj. Jose Enrique Munguia Berrios. 
He allegedly led the patrol that killed Sandinista hero Carlos Fonseca in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
"I fought people who were armed just like me. I could have been killed just as 
easily as them," Munguia said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The number of political prisoners in Nicaragua has always been widely disputed 
and remained so Friday. Sandinista officials said that only common criminals 
and Sandinista soldiers accused of abuses remain in jail now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Eva de Chaves kneels with her son, Sergio, after he was released from 
prison in Managua as part of the Sandinista-declared amnesty. J. ALBERT DIAZ / 
Los Angeles Times; Photo, (Southland Edition) Prisoners in Managua wave to 
friends, family after release on Friday. J. ALBERT DIAZ / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
