<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROMANIA INTERIM COUNCIL VOTES TO EXPAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BUCHAREST, Romania 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Council of National Unity, formed to give all registered political parties 
a say in governing Romania until the May elections, held its first meeting 
Friday and decided to expand itself by a third to 241 members. 
</P>
<P>
Interim President Ion Iliescu, who led organizational talks in the former 
National Assembly building, apparently will lead the council, but no formal 
vote was taken. 
</P>
<P>
The Assembly building is being used for the first time since the uprising 
against Communist dictator Nicolae Ceausescu, who was overthrown Dec. 22 and 
executed with his wife, Elena, on Christmas Day. It also is the first time 
since the revolution that opposition groups have had a role in leadership. 
</P>
<P>
After heated debate on whether new organizations representing ethnic minorities 
should be admitted, the council voted to expand its size from 180 to 241. A 
statement issued later said some delegates wanted the new groups limited to 
observer status. 
</P>
<P>
As envisaged in the original 180-seat council, political parties and the 
non-party bloc each were to get 90 seats. 
</P>
<P>
In the expanded 241-seat Council agreed upon Friday, 105 seats will go to 35 
parties. Nine organizations representing ethnic minorities will get 27 seats, 
three will go to former political prisoners and 106 are assigned to prominent 
Romanians who were part of the National Salvation Front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021090-0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 174411 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 10, 1990, Saturday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
